1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,680
PADs die and get replaced. Their IPs change. Services don't. Here's the problem. Your

2
00:00:09,680 --> 00:00:16,200
front-end hardcodes a back-end PAD IP. That PAD dies, a new one starts with a different

3
00:00:16,200 --> 00:00:24,280
IP, your front-end breaks. Services fix this with a stable virtual IP and DNS name. Add

4
00:00:24,280 --> 00:00:31,600
a selector to match PADs by label. Kubernetes creates a cluster IP, a stable virtual address.

5
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:38,920
CubeProxy writes network rules on every node. Traffic hits the service IP. It routes to a

6
00:00:38,920 --> 00:00:45,320
healthy PAD. Endpoint slices track which PADs back the service, updated automatically.

7
00:00:45,320 --> 00:00:53,800
Vore service types. Cluster IP internal only. The default. Node port exposes on each node.

8
00:00:53,800 --> 00:01:03,560
Port 30,000 to 32,767. Load balancer. Cloud provider creates an external load balancer.

9
00:01:03,560 --> 00:01:11,640
External name maps to an external DNS name. One service, many PADs, zero hardcoded IPs.

10
00:01:11,640 --> 00:01:19,680
That's how Kubernetes decouples your front-end from your back-end. Run the dark's Kubernetes services.

